<div class="list-title mathjax">
<span class="descriptor">Title:</span> Comment on &quot;Axion induced oscillating electric dipole moments&quot;
</div>
<div class="list-authors">
<span class="descriptor">Authors:</span> 
<a href="/find/hep-ph/1/au:+Flambaum_V/0/1/0/all/0/1">V. V. Flambaum</a>, 
<a href="/find/hep-ph/1/au:+Roberts_B/0/1/0/all/0/1">B. M. Roberts</a>, 
<a href="/find/hep-ph/1/au:+Stadnik_Y/0/1/0/all/0/1">Y. V. Stadnik</a>
</div>
<div class="list-comments">
<span class="descriptor">Comments:</span> 2 pages. Version accepted for publication as a Comment in Physical Review D
</div>
<div class="list-journal-ref">
<span class="descriptor">Journal-ref:</span> Physical Review D 95, 058701 (2017)
</div>
<div class="list-subjects">
<span class="descriptor">Subjects:</span> <span class="primary-subject">High Energy Physics - Phenomenology (hep-ph)</span>; Cosmology and Nongalactic Astrophysics (astro-ph.CO); Atomic Physics (physics.atom-ph)

</div>
<p class="mathjax">In the recent work [Phys. Rev. D 91, 111702(R) (2015)], C. Hill concludes
that the axion electromagnetic anomaly induces an oscillating electron electric
dipole moment of frequency $m_a$ and strength $\sim 10^{-32}~e$ cm, in the
limit $v/c \to 0$ for the axion field. Here, we demonstrate that a proper
treatment of this problem in the lowest order yields $\textit{no}$ electric
dipole moment of the electron in the same limit. Instead, oscillating electric
dipole moments of atoms and molecules are produced by different mechanisms.
</p>
</div>
